      },
      "lineNbr": 577,
      "author": {
        "id": 5045
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-12-14T17:37:55Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I think I\u0027m skipping ahead here just from the way diffs are showing up in the code review, but since I\u0027m here.... this sort of thing feels like it wants to be way more up-front in the compiler, enforcing the language rules in the frontend rather than each backend?  I would expect the only errors we\u0027d have in this file are of the not-yet-implemented variety?\n\nThe main reason I ask is, is this sort of thing what\u0027s putting such a heavy burden on the callers of writeExpression() to always check for errors?  If there were one or two exceptional places that needed error-checking, sure, but as it is it looks easy to forget to check _and_ very likely that if you do forget to check, you\u0027ll blow up.  If we\u0027re going to be very likely errorful, let\u0027s make writeExpression() return a std::tuple\u003cValue,bool\u003e or something so you have to actively unpack the value and error and really choose to ignore the error?",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 567,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 577,
        "endChar": 0
      },
      "revId": "2929504dbcf5dd9e57f6c57384f64ad680713f32",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "99e63aa2_ffaae88b",
        "filename": "src/sksl/SkSLVMGenerator.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 19
      },
      "lineNbr": 577,
      "author": {
        "id": 5631
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-12-14T19:53:24Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "You\u0027re right about this - these rules do need to be enforced in the front-end. This is actually a subset of a larger class of things that need to be prevented in the front-end (for runtime effects): all bitwise integer operators.\n\nGLES 2.0 doesn\u0027t allow any bitwise ops (though the integer type does exist, and arithmetic can be used). This is their concession to the fact that hardware may not have had actual integers, and could be approximating it using floats. (skbug.com/11088)",
      "parentUuid": "4c9743a3_ba9dcebe",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 567,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 577,
        "endChar": 0
      },
      "revId": "2929504dbcf5dd9e57f6c57384f64ad680713f32",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "0c8018ae_ccf5123b",
        "filename": "src/sksl/SkSLVMGenerator.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 19
      },
      "lineNbr": 577,
      "author": {
        "id": 5045
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-12-14T21:01:25Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "sgtm.\n\nIn case it wasn\u0027t obvious, this comment here was really just me happening to glance at a chunk of code near an unrelated edit in the diff view.  I would like to push all the language enforcement to the frontend, if there are any other rules.  By the time we get here I don\u0027t want to fail for language reasons.  (Though I don\u0027t at all mind _asserting_ language rules are followed in the backends.)  It\u0027s just that if we enforce rules in the backends, we\u0027ll end up enforcing subtly different rules in each.\n\nIncidentally, skvm could support shifts by variables like `I32 sra(I32, I32)` if we want.  In practice they weren\u0027t needed for Skia\u0027s effects, but we can do them if useful.",
      "parentUuid": "99e63aa2_ffaae88b",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 567,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 577,
        "endChar": 0
      },
      "revId": "2929504dbcf5dd9e57f6c57384f64ad680713f32",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "5f018075_81e7524c",
        "filename": "src/sksl/SkSLVMGenerator.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 19
      },
      "lineNbr": 577,
      "author": {
        "id": 5631
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-12-14T22:15:33Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Agreed about enforcement - having late-stage enforcement like this has been a problem in the past - it\u0027s always too late to do anything (or really let the user know). I\u0027ve got a set of bugs to address some of these, but I am planning on a series of CLs to enforce all of these kinds of rules up front, so that we\u0027re not producing errors at this stage.",
      "parentUuid": "0c8018ae_ccf5123b",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 567,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 577,
        "endChar": 0
      },
      "revId": "2929504dbcf5dd9e57f6c57384f64ad680713f32",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "bfced628_7dd8bc49",
        "filename": "src/sksl/SkSLVMGenerator.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 19
      },
      "lineNbr": 1235,
      "author": {
        "id": 5045
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-12-14T17:37:55Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Some of this feels like fluff that\u0027s made it through a layer of the compiler it didn\u0027t need to... can\u0027t we just rewrite all these as (0-x) and (~0^x) as we see them in the frontend?",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 1222,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 1235,
        "endChar": 70
      },
      "revId": "2929504dbcf5dd9e57f6c57384f64ad680713f32",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "c88616e9_9ddcdf7a",
        "filename": "src/sksl/SkSLVMGenerator.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 19
      },
      "lineNbr": 1426,
      "author": {
        "id": 5045
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-12-14T17:37:55Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Out of curiosity, what are the semantics of discard?  Different from return {0,0,0,0}?",
      "revId": "2929504dbcf5dd9e57f6c57384f64ad680713f32",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "b108a7c0_73d568f0",
        "filename": "src/sksl/SkSLVMGenerator.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 19
      },
      "lineNbr": 1426,
      "author": {
        "id": 5631
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-12-14T19:53:24Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Yes, it actually kills that particular pixel (so no writes happen to any buffers). It\u0027s a statement type that shouldn\u0027t even be permitted in public SkSL - though it is today). Filed skbug.com/11085",
      "parentUuid": "c88616e9_9ddcdf7a",
      "revId": "2929504dbcf5dd9e57f6c57384f64ad680713f32",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "922f9ac6_e19d92b4",
        "filename": "src/sksl/SkSLVMGenerator.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 19
      },
      "lineNbr": 1426,
      "author": {
        "id": 5045
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-12-14T21:01:25Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Ah.  That\u0027s interesting.  Of course I\u0027m ok to kill it.\n\nBut now hypothetically if we didn\u0027t, we\u0027d need to track another discard mask kind of how we do for knowing if a value\u0027s already returned, right?  And return that mask along with the color, and it becomes the blitter\u0027s job to handle things from there?\n\nIt\u0027s a short step away from there to returning a color and its coverage from the shader, where today\u0027s ordinary path is 1.0, discard is 0.0, and something new happens in the middle.",
      "parentUuid": "b108a7c0_73d568f0",
      "revId": "2929504dbcf5dd9e57f6c57384f64ad680713f32",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": false,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "90e44d8f_32160960",
        "filename": "src/sksl/SkSLVMGenerator.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 19
      },
      "lineNbr": 1426,
      "author": {
        "id": 5631
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-12-14T22:15:33Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Yeah, after I filed the bug, I waffled briefly and thought that we could let users write discard. As you point out, that lets people control coverage. Of course, it would happen somewhat silently from the SkShader side of things (unless we surfaced that), and could end up violating some existing analysis we do. (eg: a full-screen draw in kSrc mode means we can throw away all previous draw ops). So for now, I\u0027m going to hide it - we\u0027d need to be pretty deliberate about exposing it, given the Skia drawing model.",
      "parentUuid": "922f9ac6_e19d92b4",
      "revId": "2929504dbcf5dd9e57f6c57384f64ad680713f32",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "6b205329_edee70ad",
        "filename": "src/sksl/SkSLVMGenerator.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 19
      },
      "lineNbr": 1430,
      "author": {
        "id": 5045
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-12-14T17:37:55Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "This is of course moot given that these are all unhandled, but is there not some sort of unifying representation for do/for/while?  I\u0027d have expected everything to be reduced to while loops by the frontend.  Is there value in preserving the original control flow construct?",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 1427,
        "startChar": 8,
        "endLine": 1430,
        "endChar": 37
      },
      "revId": "2929504dbcf5dd9e57f6c57384f64ad680713f32",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "253fd72c_c95e10a5",
        "filename": "src/sksl/SkSLVMGenerator.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 19
      },
      "lineNbr": 1430,
      "author": {
        "id": 5631
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-12-14T22:15:33Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "This (and some other things you pointed out) reflect that the IR today is largely modeled around GLSL (syntax, not just semantics). In this case, there are some GPU profiles that only support for loops (and restricted for loops, at that).",
      "parentUuid": "6b205329_edee70ad",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 1427,
        "startChar": 8,
        "endLine": 1430,
        "endChar": 37
      },
      "revId": "2929504dbcf5dd9e57f6c57384f64ad680713f32",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "1c4a7ea4_65c67d53",
        "filename": "src/sksl/SkSLVMGenerator.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 19
      },
      "lineNbr": 1430,
      "author": {
        "id": 5045
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-12-14T22:40:15Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Oh sure... what I really mean is that it\u0027s straightforward both to transform a for-loop into a while-loop and to do the opposite from while to for.  They\u0027re two ways of expressing the same core concept, and even do-loops boil down to that with a little pre-patch bit of code that runs once unconditionally.  So I found it surprising that we\u0027ve got hooks to handle the three differently, as if we\u0027d need to.  It just seems like we\u0027re setting ourselves up to have bugs creep into whichever loop construct is least often used.",
      "parentUuid": "253fd72c_c95e10a5",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 1427,
        "startChar": 8,
        "endLine": 1430,
        "endChar": 37
      },
      "revId": "2929504dbcf5dd9e57f6c57384f64ad680713f32",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02"
    },
